@JonZeolla and I have been using shellcheck for all of our bro testing scripts, and I used it for the RC scripts and the common script as well.  I don't think I would call the existing bash scripts style and practice.

I think it is a good practice, and makes it really clear for everyone contributing to script code what is required.

That being said, it is _not_ the project standard, so I can't make you do it.

@nickwallen I made the change as promised above, but the build for centos6 fails for me. I tried troubleshooting locally, but I'm clueless why I'm running into an issue here. The error is pretty cryptic to me:

```
"[INFO] metron-rpm ......................................... FAILURE [03:43 min]", "[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------", "[INFO] BUILD FAILURE", "[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------", "[INFO] Total time: 03:45 min (Wall Clock)", "[INFO] Finished at: 2019-11-06T16:01:01-06:00", "[INFO] Final Memory: 14M/245M", "[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------", "[ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.codehaus.mojo:exec-maven-plugin:1.5.0:exec (rpm-build) on project metron-rpm: Command execution failed. Process exited with an error: 1 (Exit value: 1) -> [Help 1]", "[ERROR] ", "[ERROR] To see the full stack trace of the errors, re-run Maven with the -e switch.", "[ERROR] Re-run Maven using the -X switch to enable full debug logging.", "[ERROR] ", "[ERROR] For more information about the errors and possible solutions, please read the following articles:", "[ERROR] [Help 1] http://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/MAVEN/MojoExecutionException", "[ERROR] ", "[ERROR] After correcting the problems, you can resume the build with the command", "[ERROR]   mvn <goals> -rf :metron-rpm"]}
```

I tested the curl script and it seems to work fine. Any chance I could get you to give it a go locally and see if you can make any sense of it?

@mmiklavc Unfortunately, this is how every PR has been when merging master into the feature branch. For example: https://github.com/apache/metron/pull/1507/commits

As you can see, a lot of the commits listed here were merged into the feature branch already. Unfortunately, the squash merge does not retain the history in the feature branch. It gets even more complicated by the fact that we had to cherry-pick & re-write commits to accommodate the Apache attribution standards of the project.

If there were no conflicts, I would merge master into the feature and push directly upstream, but since there are so many conflicts I followed previous examples of feature branch work like this one here by @nickwallen (which also contains a lot of commits unrelated to the PR): https://github.com/apache/metron/pull/1502
